# Web app stack standard (Kurator-derived)

Use this as the default shape for new **web + API** work unless a product explicitly diverges.

## Core architecture

- **API**: Dedicated HTTP service (REST or RPC-shaped JSON), own process and config, state in **PostgreSQL** (migrations owned by the API or a shared migration tool).
- **Web**: **Next.js** App Router; **TypeScript**; styling with **Tailwind** (current major in repo).
- **Search / async**: Optional dedicated services (e.g. Meilisearch, queues) behind clear interfaces; do not embed vendor SDKs in UI for server-only work.
- **Edge / TLS**: Production routing and certificates (e.g. Traefik, platform ingress) live **outside** app code; app services listen on internal ports only.

## Repository layout (Kurator monorepo)

Default **two-app monorepo** at repo root; new products can mirror this shape.

```text
.
├── .cursor/rules/              # Cursor rules (e.g. this stack standard)
├── .github/workflows/          # ci-release, snyk, portainer-redeploy-on-release
├── api/                        # Go module (single module root)
│   ├── cmd/api/                # HTTP server entry
│   ├── cmd/migrate/            # Migrations CLI (DATABASE_URL)
│   ├── internal/               # handler, service, repository, middleware, config, migrate, …
│   ├── migrations/             # Versioned SQL (+ embed for bootstrap)
│   ├── docs/swagger.json       # OpenAPI spec (Swagger UI mounts this in infra)
│   ├── Dockerfile
│   ├── Makefile                # build, test, vet, cross-compile targets
│   └── go.mod / go.sum
├── web/                        # Next.js app
│   ├── app/                    # App Router: routes, layouts, server components
│   │   └── api/                # Route handlers (e.g. v1 proxy, unsplash, …)
│   ├── components/             # Shared UI
│   ├── lib/                    # Clients, helpers, `apiUrl`, validation, tests colocated *.test.ts
│   ├── content/                # Static markdown sources (e.g. privacy policy)
│   ├── public/                 # Static assets
│   ├── Dockerfile
│   ├── vitest.config.ts / vitest.setup.ts
│   └── package.json / package-lock.json
├── infra/
│   ├── docker-compose.yml      # Local backing services (Postgres, Meili, Valkey, Swagger)
│   └── nginx/                  # Optional sample config (not wired by default)
├── docker-compose.yml          # Production-oriented stack (e.g. Traefik + GHCR images)
├── Makefile                    # Delegates to api/; web-test at repo root
├── README.md
└── memory.md                   # Project memory for agents (optional per repo)
```

## Browser ↔ API (auth and cookies)

- Browser calls **same-origin** `/api/v1/...` (or equivalent prefix). **Next.js route handlers** proxy to the real API so **session cookies stay on the web origin** (HTTP-only, `Secure` in production).
- **Native and other non-browser clients** may call the API host directly and send **`Authorization: Bearer <session_token>`**; the opaque **`session_token`** is returned in JSON from successful auth endpoints alongside **`Set-Cookie`** (same backing session as the **`kurator_session`** cookie). See **`api/docs/swagger.json`** (`SessionCookie` and **`BearerToken`** security definitions).
- Do not point the browser client directly at a separate API host for authenticated flows unless CORS, cookie `Domain`/`SameSite`, and CSRF are fully designed for that.
- Server Components / server actions use an **internal base URL** (e.g. `API_INTERNAL_URL`) distinct from public build-time vars when the proxy is not used on the server path.

## External tooling (env and responsibility split)

| Integration | Server-only | Public / build-time | Notes |
|-------------|-------------|---------------------|--------|
| **S3-compatible storage** | Access key, secret, bucket, endpoint, optional prefix | **Only** if needed: public asset base URL for absolute links | Never expose write keys to the client. Prefer presigned URLs or public-read objects only where appropriate. |
| **Cloudflare Turnstile** | Secret key; verify token on the API for login/register/sensitive POSTs | Site key (`NEXT_PUBLIC_*`) for widget | Feature-flag or env-gate both sides so local dev can disable. |
| **Sentry** | Server DSN, environment, release | `NEXT_PUBLIC_*` DSN for browser SDK | Initialize once per runtime; avoid PII in breadcrumbs. |
| **LaunchDarkly** | Optional Node/server SDK for secure flag evaluation | Client-side ID (`NEXT_PUBLIC_*`) for React SDK | Prefer server evaluation for sensitive flags; client for UI toggles only. |

## Local development

- Prefer **Podman** + Compose for backing services (Postgres, object store, search, Redis/Valkey, etc.); keep **secrets out of compose files** — interpolate from env or secret stores. Repo root: **`make infra-up`** / **`make infra-down`** (`infra/docker-compose.yml`; override with `COMPOSE='docker compose'` if needed).
- Web dev server and API run on host (or in containers) with **documented env vars**; parity with production names where possible.
- **API live reload:** [Air](https://github.com/air-verse/air) via `api/.air.toml` — `make api-dev` from repo root or `make dev` in `api/` (install: `go install github.com/air-verse/air@latest`).

## Makefile structure and behaviour

### Design

- **Root `Makefile`**: thin **facade** — delegates almost everything to **`api/Makefile`** via **`$(MAKE) -C api <target>`** so developers run **`make api-build`** from the repo root without remembering paths.
- **`api/Makefile`**: owns **Go** build flags, output **`api/bin/`**, cross-compilation matrix, **`go test` / `go vet`**, and **`make dev`** (Air live reload).
- **Web**: day-to-day commands stay **`npm run dev`**, **`npm run build`**, **`npm test`** inside **`web/`**; the root Makefile exposes **`web-test`** only so **`make api-test`** and **`make web-test`** sit side by side in **`help`** and CI docs.
- **`.PHONY`**: declare every recipe name that is not a real file at both levels to avoid stale “up to date” skips.

### Root targets (repo `Makefile`)

| Target | Behaviour |
|--------|------------|
| **`help`** | Prints short descriptions; points to **`api/Makefile`** for platform-specific build targets. |
| **`api-build`** | `make -C api build` → native **`api/bin/kurator-api`**. |
| **`api-build-macos`** | `make -C api build-macos-native` (Intel vs Apple Silicon from **`uname -m`**). |
| **`api-build-linux`** | `make -C api build-linux-amd64 build-linux-arm64`. |
| **`api-build-all`** | `make -C api build-all` (darwin + linux, amd64 + arm64). |
| **`api-test`** | `make -C api test` → **`go test ./...`** from **`api/`**. |
| **`api-clean`** | `make -C api clean` → removes **`api/bin/`**. |
| **`web-test`** | **`cd web && npm test`** (Vitest **`run`** via **`package.json`**). |

Add new **cross-cutting** shortcuts at the root only when they improve discoverability; put **API-only** logic in **`api/Makefile`**.

### `api/Makefile` (Go module)

| Area | Behaviour |
|------|------------|
| **Variables** | **`BINARY_NAME`** / **`CMD_PATH`** (main server), **`BIN_DIR := bin`**, **`LDFLAGS := -s -w`**, **`GOFLAGS := -trimpath`**. |
| **`build`** | **`CGO_ENABLED=0`** **`go build`** → **`$(BIN_DIR)/$(BINARY_NAME)`** (portable static linking style). |
| **Cross-compile** | Per-OS/arch recipes (**`build-darwin-amd64`**, **`build-darwin-arm64`**, **`build-linux-amd64`**, **`build-linux-arm64`**); **`build-all`** runs all four; **`build-macos-native`** picks one based on host. |
| **`test` / `vet` / `clean`** | **`go test ./...`**, **`go vet ./...`**, **`rm -rf $(BIN_DIR)`**. |
| **`swagger`** | Echo-only: OpenAPI path, how to run **Swagger UI** via **infra** compose, optional **swag** regen reminder (spec file is source of truth in **`api/docs/swagger.json`**). |
## Testing suites (match CI)

### API (Go)

- **Runner**: `go test` from the **`api/`** module root (`make api-test` from repo root).
- **Scope**: all packages; use **`-count=1`** in CI to disable cache and catch flakes.
- **Layout**: colocated **`*_test.go`** next to production code (e.g. `internal/handler`, `internal/service`, `internal/config`, `internal/migrate`, `internal/models`, `internal/validation`). No separate `tests/` tree required.
- **Style**: table-driven and focused unit tests; mock external HTTP/S3 where needed; avoid requiring Postgres in unit tests unless you add a dedicated integration job.

### Web (Next.js)

- **Runner**: **Vitest** with **`@vitejs/plugin-react`**, **`jsdom`**, **`@testing-library/react`** + **`@testing-library/jest-dom`** (`npm test` / `make web-test`).
- **Config**: `web/vitest.config.ts` — `include: **/*.{test,spec}.{ts,tsx}`, `exclude: .next`, path alias `@` → `web/`.
- **Setup**: `web/vitest.setup.ts` — jest-dom matchers, Testing Library **`configure({ reactStrictMode: false })`** to avoid double-mount issues with controlled inputs, **`afterEach(cleanup)`**.
- **What to test**: pure **`lib/`** helpers (URLs, validation, labels), and shallow component behavior with **`vi.mock`** for `next/navigation`, auth hooks, and heavy child widgets.

### Optional extensions

- **ESLint**: `npm run lint` in `web/` (run locally / add a CI job if you want lint to gate merges).
- **E2E** (Playwright, Cypress): not part of the default Kurator CI; add a workflow + install only when a product needs browser automation.

## GitHub Actions patterns (`.github/workflows/`)

Shared conventions across workflows:

- **`concurrency`**: `group: ${{ github.workflow }}-${{ github.ref }}` with **`cancel-in-progress: true`** so new pushes supersede stale runs.
- **Commit skip**: a **`check-skip`** job sets **`should_skip`** when the **latest commit message** matches **`^(CI|INFO):`** — use for docs-only or automation commits that should not run tests, builds, or Snyk. Downstream jobs **`if: needs.check-skip.outputs.should_skip != 'true'`**.

### `ci-release.yml` (CI + release)

- **Triggers**: `push` to **`main`**, all **`pull_request`**, **`workflow_dispatch`**.
- **`unit-tests`**: checkout → **`actions/setup-go`** with **`go-version-file: api/go.mod`** → `go test ./... -count=1` in **`api/`** → **`actions/setup-node`** (Node **22**, npm cache on **`web/package-lock.json`**) → `npm ci && npm test` in **`web/`**.
- **`release`** (only when not skipped, **`github.ref == refs/heads/main`**, event **`push`** or **`workflow_dispatch`**): SemVer tag bump (**`mathieudutour/github-tag-action`** with custom rules mapping **`MAJOR`/`MINOR`/`PATCH`** commit prefixes); cross-compile **API** `linux/darwin` × **`amd64`/`arm64`** with **`CGO_ENABLED=0`**; **GitHub Release** + artifact upload; optional **`aws s3 cp`** of legal/static copy (e.g. privacy markdown) when **`S3_*`** secrets exist; **Docker Buildx** login **GHCR**; **`docker/build-push-action`** for **`api`** and **`web`** images with versioned + **`latest`** tags and **build-args** for internal API URL, **`NEXT_PUBLIC_*`** (Sentry, LaunchDarkly, Brandfetch), **Sentry** org/project/auth for web source maps if used.

### `snyk.yml` (security)

- **Triggers**: PR, push to **`main`**, **`workflow_dispatch`**, **weekly cron** (e.g. Mondays 09:00 UTC).
- **Fork PRs**: Snyk job **`if`** excludes **`pull_request`** from forks (`head.repo.full_name == github.repository`) so **`SNYK_TOKEN`** is not exposed to untrusted code.
- **Steps**: **`snyk test`** in **`api/`** and **`web/`** (after **`npm ci`** in web); **`snyk code test`** at repo root; **`snyk monitor`** only on **`push`** to **`main`** to refresh Snyk project metadata.

### `portainer-redeploy-on-release.yml` (deploy hook)

- **Trigger**: **`release`** **`published`**.
- **Skip**: same **`CI`/`INFO`** prefix check on the **tag’s** commit message.
- **`redeploy-stack`**: **`curl`** Portainer API (**`PORTAINER_URL`**, **`PORTAINER_API_TOKEN`**, **`PORTAINER_STACK_ID`**); optional **`PORTAINER_TLS_INSECURE`**; parse **`EndpointId`** with inline **Python** JSON.
- **`notify-discord`**: optional **`DISCORD_WEBHOOK_URL`** posting trimmed release notes.

## When adding a new integration

1. Classify **server vs client** secrets and document both in README / example env.
2. Add **health or startup checks** where the service degrades without the integration (optional S3, optional search).
3. Add **tests** for parsing, URL building, and feature flags at the unit level; avoid live vendor calls in unit tests.
4. If the integration touches dependencies, ensure **`snyk.yml`** still covers the right directory (`snyk test` from that folder after install).
